#
# moty CLI surface (decoded from POSITIONAL/
# ARGUMENTS/FLAGS aliases at config.mojo:4-6 +
# usage in Config constructor):
#   <path>                   positional path to Python file to check
#   --log-type=silent|verbose log type (default: silent)
#   --strict                 enable strict type checking (boolean flag)
#
# moty is a Python static type checker written in
# Mojo — checks Python source files for type
# errors using Mojo's compile-time type system.
# Authored by Samuel Ibarra (IbarraSamuel).  0 GH
# stars (recent project).  Sister tools: mypy
# (mature Python type checker, in corpus),
# pyright (Microsoft Python type checker, in
# corpus), ruff (Python linter, in corpus).
#
# Critical extraction note: moty uses **Mojo
# stdlib `sys.argv()` primitive + handwritten
# parametric `collect_args` function with
# compile-time `alias` spec lists** at cli.mojo:1+
# config.mojo:4-6 — corpus's **first documented
# Mojo CLI pattern**.  Mojo has NO FORMAL CLI
# library in its stdlib (Mojo is too new — v0.26
# stdlib has just `sys.argv()` primitive
# returning `List[StaticString]`).  moty's
# approach: define COMPILE-TIME `alias` lists for
# POSITIONAL, ARGUMENTS, and FLAGS spec, then
# pass them as COMPILE-TIME TYPE PARAMETERS to a
# generic `collect_args[positional, arguments,
# flags]()` function.  The parser walks the argv
# at runtime but the SPEC is COMPILED IN.
# Distinct from R311 Guile `(getopt-long args
# SPEC)` (runtime spec data), R317 Forth/Gforth
# `next-arg` + handwritten matching (no spec
# data), R313 Idris 2 `MkOpt SHORT_CHARS
# LONG_STRINGS ArgDescr HELP` (runtime spec
# data), R272 C POSIX getopt (runtime option-
# string).  Mojo's approach: COMPILE-TIME
# `alias` LISTS + PARAMETRIC PARSER FUNCTION —
# corpus's **first documented compile-time-list-
# as-parameter CLI pattern**.  Extends cross-
# language CLI taxonomy to SIXTY library
# variants: Rust (6), Go (4), Python (3),
# Crystal 1 OptionParser (R269), Haskell (R270),
# OCaml (R271), C (R272), Java (R276),
# Kotlin (R277), Scala (R278), Dart (R279),
# Ruby (R280), Perl (R281), PHP (R282),
# Swift (R283), F# (R284), Lua (R285), C# (R286),
# Nim 1 parseopt (R287), Zig (R288), D (R289),
# Racket (R290), Common Lisp 1 (R291),
# Erlang (R292), Tcl (R293), Pharo Smalltalk (R294),
# Common Lisp 2 clingon (R295), Julia (R296),
# SWI-Prolog optparse (R297), Pony stdlib cli (R298),
# Crystal 2 Admiral (R299), V stdlib `flag` (R300),
# Nim 2 cligen (R301), Clojure 1 babashka.cli
# (R302), Gleam Glint (R303), Ada GNAT.Command_
# Line (R304), C++ 1 CLI11 (R305), Elixir Optimus
# (R306), Vala GLib.OptionContext (R307), Hare
# stdlib getopt (R308), Standard ML stdlib GetOpt
# (R309), Fortran M_CLI2 (R310), Guile (ice-9
# getopt-long) (R311), Free Pascal TCustomApplication
# (R312), Idris 2 System.GetOpts (R313), Mercury
# stdlib getopt_io (R314), Eiffel Gobo AP_PARSER
# (R315), C++ 2 boost::program_options (R316),
# Forth/Gforth `next-arg` (R317), Clojure 2
# org.clojure/tools.cli (R318), Roc weaver (R319),
